@eickenberg I know nothing about this, but I can see how, if the locations of the atoms are known (and they are, in the case of a known molecule), it might make sense to only evaluate U at the nuclei of these atoms, and then derive some quantum chemical properties out of the scattering coefficients of "each atom".
Likewise, in the foveated scattering of Mathieu and Ravi, the "points" method is used for prediction: causal wavelets (truncated Gabors) estimate U0 at t=0 (in other words, the present time) to predict the value of x at t=delta for small delta. So having a `points` in 1D would also make sense for that.

These are just my 2c. I defer the decision to @gexarcha @louity @eickenberg  and possibly @AndreuxMath and @beedotkiran too
